values.value:
== LWC — LIGHTNING WEB COMPONENT GENERATION ==

== FILE STRUCTURE ==
Every LWC requires EXACTLY THREE file entries in files[]:

  1. metadataType: LwcHtml   filePath: lwc/{name}/{name}.html     → HTML template source
  2. metadataType: LwcJs     filePath: lwc/{name}/{name}.js       → JavaScript source
  3. metadataType: LwcMeta   filePath: lwc/{name}/{name}.js-meta.xml → XML only

The field in the JSON response for all three is "xmlContent" (consistent with all other types).
NEVER put <?xml into a .html or .js file.
NEVER put <template> or import statements into a .js-meta.xml file.

Component naming rules:
- DeveloperName (memberName): camelCase, starts lowercase, no spaces (e.g. accountCard)
- If ticket says "Account Card" → memberName = accountCard
- If ticket says "AccountCard" → memberName = accountCard (lowercase first letter)

== JS-META.XML FORMAT ==
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<LightningComponentBundle xmlns="http://soap.sforce.com/2006/04/metadata">
    <apiVersion>61.0</apiVersion>
    <isExposed>true</isExposed>
    <targets>
        <target>lightning__RecordPage</target>
        <target>lightning__AppPage</target>
    </targets>
</LightningComponentBundle>

Target selection rules:
- Default (ticket does not specify): lightning__RecordPage + lightning__AppPage
- "Record page" or "on the account/contact/case record": lightning__RecordPage only
- "App page" or "home page" or "utility bar": use the matching target
- "Flow screen": lightning__FlowScreen only
- NEVER include <targetConfigs> — keep meta simple

== DEPLOYMENT PLAN ==
LWC-only deploys always use scenario = "single".
If the ticket also creates a new CustomObject: object in ZIP1, layout in ZIP2, LWC always in ZIP1.

== MERGE MODE vs CREATE MODE ==
The decision is made ENTIRELY from org state — ticket wording does NOT override it.

STEP ZERO — CHECK orgState.existingLwcComponent BEFORE WRITING ANYTHING.

  IF orgState.existingLwcComponent IS NOT NULL → MERGE MODE (see below)
  IF orgState.existingLwcComponent IS NULL     → CREATE MODE (see below)

Words like "create an LWC", "build a component", "add an LWC" describe BUSINESS INTENT.
If existingLwcComponent is not null, you are ALWAYS in MERGE MODE regardless of ticket wording.

-- MERGE MODE — existingLwcComponent IS NOT NULL --
STEP 1: List every section and element in existingLwcComponent.html. ALL must appear in output.
STEP 2: List every import, property (@api, @track, @wire), and method in existingLwcComponent.js. ALL must appear in output.
STEP 3: Identify what the ticket is adding or changing.
STEP 4: Start from existingLwcComponent.html verbatim. Apply only the requested change.
STEP 5: Start from existingLwcComponent.js verbatim. Apply only the requested change.
STEP 6: SELF-CHECK:
  - Does output HTML contain every section from STEP 1? If not, add missing ones.
  - Does output JS contain every import and method from STEP 2? If not, paste them back.
  - Is output the COMPLETE file — not a snippet?
STEP 7: Emit all three files (html, js, meta). The meta file may be unchanged — still include it.

-- CREATE MODE — existingLwcComponent IS NULL --
Generate all three files from scratch.
Use the component name from orgState or infer from ticket context.

== TIER 1 — WIRE-BASED (no Apex, read-only display) ==
Use when: ticket asks to display record fields, related list, or object data.
No Apex class needed.

-- TEMPLATE PATTERN (Tier 1) --
<template>
    <lightning-card title="Card Title" icon-name="standard:account">
        <div class="slds-p-around_medium">
            <template if:true={record.data}>
                <p><strong>Name:</strong> {name}</p>
                <p><strong>Industry:</strong> {industry}</p>
            </template>
            <template if:true={record.error}>
                <p class="slds-text-color_error">Error loading data.</p>
            </template>
        </div>
    </lightning-card>
</template>

-- JS PATTERN (Tier 1, getRecord wire) --
import { LightningElement, api, wire } from 'lwc';
import { getRecord } from 'lightning/uiRecordApi';
import NAME_FIELD from '@salesforce/schema/Account.Name';
import INDUSTRY_FIELD from '@salesforce/schema/Account.Industry';

export default class AccountCard extends LightningElement {
    @api recordId;

    @wire(getRecord, { recordId: '$recordId', fields: [NAME_FIELD, INDUSTRY_FIELD] })
    record;

    get name() {
        return this.record.data?.fields?.Name?.value;
    }

    get industry() {
        return this.record.data?.fields?.Industry?.value;
    }
}

TIER 1 RULES:
- Use @api recordId when the component lives on a record page
- Import each field separately using @salesforce/schema/ObjectName.FieldName
- Use optional chaining (?.) when reading wire data fields
- Use if:true={record.data} and if:true={record.error} — ALWAYS both, never one without the other
- Never hardcode record IDs

== TIER 2 — APEX-CONNECTED (imperative Apex, loading state) ==
Use when: ticket asks to display data that requires custom SOQL, DML, or business logic.
An Apex controller MUST be generated or read.

TIER 2 USES IMPERATIVE APEX — NOT @wire.
Do NOT use @wire in a Tier 2 component. Do NOT import wire from 'lwc' in Tier 2.
The correct import line for Tier 2 is EXACTLY:
  import { LightningElement, api, track } from 'lwc';
If you add wire to that import, you are doing it wrong.

-- TEMPLATE PATTERN (Tier 2) --
<template>
    <lightning-card title="Invoice List" icon-name="standard:invoice">
        <div class="slds-p-around_medium">
            <template if:true={isLoading}>
                <lightning-spinner alternative-text="Loading" size="small"></lightning-spinner>
            </template>
            <template if:true={error}>
                <p class="slds-text-color_error">{error}</p>
            </template>
            <template if:true={invoices}>
                <template for:each={invoices} for:item="inv">
                    <p key={inv.Id}>{inv.Name} — {inv.Amount__c}</p>
                </template>
            </template>
        </div>
    </lightning-card>
</template>

-- JS PATTERN (Tier 2, imperative Apex) --
// CORRECT Tier 2 import — no wire:
import { LightningElement, api, track } from 'lwc';
import getInvoices from '@salesforce/apex/InvoiceController.getInvoices';

export default class InvoiceList extends LightningElement {
    @api recordId;
    @track invoices;
    @track isLoading = false;
    @track error;

    connectedCallback() {
        this.loadData();
    }

    loadData() {
        this.isLoading = true;
        this.error = undefined;
        getInvoices({ accountId: this.recordId })
            .then(result => {
                this.invoices = result;
                this.isLoading = false;
            })
            .catch(err => {
                this.error = err.body?.message || 'An unexpected error occurred.';
                this.isLoading = false;
            });
    }

    // Refresh / action button handler pattern:
    // ALWAYS clear data and error first so spinner appears and user sees visual feedback.
    // ALWAYS guard with !this.isLoading to prevent double-calls.
    handleRefresh() {
        if (!this.isLoading) {
            this.invoices = undefined;
            this.error = undefined;
            this.loadData();
        }
    }
}

TIER 2 RULES:
- ALWAYS use @track for properties that drive template re-render
- ALWAYS show lightning-spinner when isLoading is true
- ALWAYS handle the .catch() — never leave it out
- ALWAYS reset error to undefined at the start of loadData()
- ALWAYS call loadData() from connectedCallback() for initial load
- Import path: @salesforce/apex/ClassName.methodName
- Use err.body?.message for error display — never err.message directly
- When a ticket asks for a Refresh/Reload button: ALWAYS clear the data property and error
  to undefined BEFORE calling loadData() — this gives visible feedback to the user.
  Without clearing, the list stays visible during reload and the button appears broken.
- When a Refresh button exists: the Apex method MUST use @AuraEnabled (NOT cacheable=true).
  @AuraEnabled(cacheable=true) with imperative calls returns platform-cached data for the
  same parameters — the Refresh button will appear to do nothing even though it runs.
  Rule: @AuraEnabled(cacheable=true) only for @wire / display-only. @AuraEnabled for any
  method that must return fresh data on demand (Refresh button, form submit, etc.).

LWC EVENT HANDLER SYNTAX — CRITICAL:
LWC uses "on" prefix for all event handlers. It does NOT support Vue.js or Angular syntax.

  CORRECT (LWC):                         WRONG (Vue/Angular — FORBIDDEN in LWC):
  onclick={handleClick}                  @click={handleClick}
  onchange={handleChange}                (change)={handleChange}
  onkeyup={handleKeyUp}                  v-on:keyup={handleKeyUp}

Button patterns (use names appropriate to the ticket):
  <lightning-button label="{ticketLabel}" onclick={handlerMethod}></lightning-button>
  <lightning-button label="{ticketLabel}" onclick={handlerMethod} disabled={isLoading}></lightning-button>

lightning-card slot placement rule:
  When a ticket asks for a button or action in the card HEADER, use slot="actions" on the element.
  Without slot="actions", any element placed inside lightning-card renders in the card BODY, not the header.
  Slot name reference: "actions" → header right area | (none) → card body | "title" → card title area

Using @click causes compile error: LWC1124 — @click is not a valid attribute.

TIER 2 TEMPLATE DATA ACCESS — CRITICAL:
In Tier 2, this.opportunities (or this.records, this.items, etc.) is a plain JavaScript Array
assigned from the imperative .then(result => { this.opportunities = result; }).
It is NOT a wire result object. It has NO .data or .error properties.

  CORRECT (Tier 2 — imperative):        WRONG (Tier 1 wire pattern — FORBIDDEN in Tier 2):
  if:true={opportunities}                if:true={opportunities.data}
  for:each={opportunities}               for:each={opportunities.data}
  if:true={error}                        if:true={opportunities.error}
  {error}                                {opportunities.error}

Using {opportunities.data} when opportunities is a plain array causes:
  "Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'data')" at connect phase.

The @wire FUNCTION HANDLER pattern also produces a plain array and has the same rules:
  @wire(getOpps, { accountId: '$recordId' })
  wiredResult({ data, error }) {
      if (data) { this.opportunities = data; }  // ← plain array, NOT {data, error} object
  }
  In this case too: template uses {opportunities} not {opportunities.data}.

If you are confused about which pattern to use: use the imperative .then().catch() pattern
(no @wire at all) — it is always safe and unambiguous for Tier 2.

== APEX CONTROLLER FOR LWC ==

-- WHEN TO READ AN EXISTING CONTROLLER --
Check orgState.existingLwcApexController.
IF NOT NULL → the class already exists in the org.
  1. Read the FULL existing body from orgState.existingLwcApexController.body
  2. Add the new method(s) the ticket requires
  3. Emit COMPLETE class — ALL existing methods preserved + new method appended
  4. Emit ApexClass + ApexClassMeta file entries (both required)

IF NULL → generate the class fresh.
  Naming rule: {ComponentName}Controller with first letter uppercase
  Example: component "invoiceList" → class "InvoiceListController"

-- APEX CONTROLLER TEMPLATE --
public with sharing class InvoiceListController {

    @AuraEnabled(cacheable=true)
    public static List<Invoice__c> getInvoices(Id accountId) {
        return [
            SELECT Id, Name, Amount__c, Status__c, CreatedDate
            FROM Invoice__c
            WHERE Account__c = :accountId
            ORDER BY CreatedDate DESC
            LIMIT 100
        ];
    }
}

-- APEX FILE ENTRIES — EXACT CONTENT ASSIGNMENT (READ THIS CAREFULLY) --
An Apex class ALWAYS requires exactly 2 file entries. The content types are OPPOSITE to what
you might expect. Swapping them is the single most common LLM mistake with Apex files.

  File 1 → metadataType: "ApexClass"
    filePath:   "classes/ClassName.cls"
    xmlContent: ← APEX SOURCE CODE (public with sharing class ...)
                   MUST start with "public" or "@isTest" or "global"
                   NEVER starts with <?xml
                   NEVER contains <ApexClass>

  File 2 → metadataType: "ApexClassMeta"
    filePath:   "classes/ClassName.cls-meta.xml"
    xmlContent: ← META XML ONLY
                   MUST start with <?xml version
                   MUST contain <ApexClass xmlns=...>
                   NEVER contains Apex code

CORRECT EXAMPLE (copy this pattern exactly):
{
  "metadataType": "ApexClass",
  "memberName": "OpportunityListController",
  "filePath": "classes/OpportunityListController.cls",
  "xmlContent": "public with sharing class OpportunityListController {\n    @AuraEnabled(cacheable=true)\n    public static List<Opportunity> getOpenOpportunities(Id accountId) {\n        return [SELECT Id, Name, Amount, StageName, CloseDate FROM Opportunity WHERE AccountId = :accountId AND IsClosed = false ORDER BY CloseDate ASC LIMIT 100];\n    }\n}"
},
{
  "metadataType": "ApexClassMeta",
  "memberName": "OpportunityListController",
  "filePath": "classes/OpportunityListController.cls-meta.xml",
  "xmlContent": "<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<ApexClass xmlns=\"http://soap.sforce.com/2006/04/metadata\">\n    <apiVersion>61.0</apiVersion>\n    <status>Active</status>\n</ApexClass>"
}

APEX CONTROLLER RULES:
- ALWAYS use "public with sharing" — never "without sharing" unless ticket explicitly requires it
- READ operations (SELECT only): @AuraEnabled(cacheable=true)
- WRITE operations (DML): @AuraEnabled — no cacheable
- NEVER put SOQL inside loops (governor limit violation)
- ALWAYS use a WHERE clause with a bound variable — never return all records without filter
- Parameters match what the LWC JS calls: getInvoices({ accountId: this.recordId })
- If ticket does not specify a class name → use {ComponentName}Controller

-- WHEN TICKET SAYS THE CLASS ALREADY EXISTS --
If the ticket explicitly says "the class already exists" or "use existing ClassName":
  1. orgState.existingLwcApexController will contain the body
  2. Do NOT regenerate it from scratch
  3. Only add the new method the ticket requests if it is not already there
  4. If the method already exists, do not duplicate it

== JEST TEST FILE (LwcTest) ==
ALWAYS generate a Jest test file for every LWC component you create or update.

File type  : LwcTest
filePath   : lwc/{componentName}/__tests__/{componentName}.test.js
memberName : {componentName}  (same as the component)

The Jest test validates the generated component logic BEFORE it is accepted.
The pipeline saves it to a ContentDocument so a local script can retrieve and run it.

-- TIER 2 JEST PATTERN --
Use this exact structure. Replace component name, import path, and mock data to match the ticket.

import { createElement } from 'lwc';
import {ComponentClassName} from 'c/{componentName}';
import {apexMethodName} from '@salesforce/apex/{ControllerName}.{methodName}';

jest.mock(
    '@salesforce/apex/{ControllerName}.{methodName}',
    () => ({ default: jest.fn() }),
    { virtual: true }
);

const MOCK_DATA = [{ Id: '0010000000001AAA', Name: 'Test Record' }];

describe('c-{component-name}', () => {
    afterEach(() => {
        while (document.body.firstChild) {
            document.body.removeChild(document.body.firstChild);
        }
        jest.clearAllMocks();
    });

    it('shows spinner on initial load before data arrives', () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockResolvedValue(MOCK_DATA);
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        const spinner = element.shadowRoot.querySelector('lightning-spinner');
        expect(spinner).not.toBeNull();
    });

    it('renders list items after successful Apex call', async () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockResolvedValue(MOCK_DATA);
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        element.recordId = '0010000000001AAA';
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        await Promise.resolve();
        const items = element.shadowRoot.querySelectorAll('li');
        expect(items.length).toBe(MOCK_DATA.length);
    });

    it('hides spinner after data loads', async () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockResolvedValue(MOCK_DATA);
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        element.recordId = '0010000000001AAA';
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        await Promise.resolve();
        const spinner = element.shadowRoot.querySelector('lightning-spinner');
        expect(spinner).toBeNull();
    });

    it('shows error paragraph when Apex call fails', async () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockRejectedValue({ body: { message: 'Server error' } });
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        element.recordId = '0010000000001AAA';
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        await Promise.resolve();
        const errorEl = element.shadowRoot.querySelector('.slds-text-color_error');
        expect(errorEl).not.toBeNull();
    });
});

JEST RULES:
- ALWAYS include the 4 core test cases: spinner shown, data rendered, spinner hidden, error shown
- ALWAYS mock every @salesforce/apex import with jest.mock({ virtual: true })
- ALWAYS clean up DOM in afterEach with document.body.removeChild loop
- ALWAYS call await Promise.resolve() after appendChild to flush microtask queue
- Use the EXACT class name and method name from the generated JS import
- Do NOT import from lwc/jest — use 'lwc' only
- The filePath MUST be: lwc/componentName/__tests__/{componentName}.test.js

== NEVER ==
- Never use @click, @change, or any @ event syntax — LWC uses onclick, onchange, etc.
- Never use @wire in a Tier 2 component — Tier 2 uses imperative .then().catch() only
- Never import wire from 'lwc' in a Tier 2 component — correct import is: import { LightningElement, api, track } from 'lwc'
- Never use {property.data} or {property.error} in a Tier 2 template — use {property} and {error} directly
- Never put <?xml into an ApexClass file — ApexClass.xmlContent MUST be Apex source code starting with "public"
- Never put Apex code (public with sharing...) into an ApexClassMeta file — its xmlContent MUST be meta XML starting with <?xml
- Never put <?xml version into a .html or .js file
- Never put <template> or import statements into a .js-meta.xml file
- Never use document.getElementById or direct DOM manipulation — use template refs
- Never leave off the error handling block in Tier 2
- Never hardcode Salesforce record IDs in JS
- Never skip the lightning-spinner in Tier 2 components
- Never use innerHTML — it is not supported in LWC
- Never forget the key={uniqueField} attribute on for:each items
- Never generate a FlexiPage XML file — out of scope; tell the user to add via App Builder manually
- Never generate a CSS file — out of scope for now
